#1 Rectal cancer with synchronous malignant polyp with uncertain margins
I discussed with Mrs. Becnel and her daughter that she predominantly has rectal cancer although she also had cancer found in the sigmoid polyp, and we have unclear margins.  She has not undergone tattooing of either of these areas and will need to go through the standard evaluation for rectal cancer including endoscopic rectal ultrasound, CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis, chest x-ray, and CEA.  We will have her see Dr. Charlie Mccloskey in surgical consultation later this week following her testing.  Discussed the possible need for neoadjuvant treatment.  Due to the location of her tumor, discussed briefly potential surgeries.  It is likely she will need a large abdominal operation, possibly a low-anterior resection versus coloanal.  I think there is a smaller chance she will need a permanent colostomy.  I will see her back with Dr. Mccloskey following her testing.  Prep instructions reviewed.   I discussed with Mrs. Becnel that her siblings need to all undergo colonoscopies if they have not done so and that her children need to start undergoing screening colonoscopies at age 48.
#2 Elevated blood pressure without hypertension
This is mild.  No further evaluation at this time.
#3 History of elevated cholesterol
This has been well-controlled on fish oil.
#4 Sore throat
I do not see evidence of pharyngitis or significant erythema of the posterior pharynx.  She does not have a fever and we will continue with the evaluation as planned.
#5 PAME
Will obtain EKG, chest x-ray, and basic blood work.
Spent 70 minutes reviewing plan of care and discussing rectal cancer evaluation in detail with Mrs. Becnel and her daughter.  All questions were answered.  Given laparoscopic colon book.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, not on file at Indian River Hospital.  She will check at-home whether she has one and bring this if she does.
Code status discussion:  Discussed with Mrs. Becnel and her daughter.  She would like to be a full code.

