[start section id="20102"]

Mrs. Becnel is seen at the request of Dr. Graver for evaluation for rectal cancer with a synchronous malignant sigmoid polyp.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Becnel is a 58-year-old female from 71016 Lancaster, with a six-month history of intermittent rectal bleeding.  She had never undergone a screening colonoscopy.  Due to her bleeding she went in for evaluation and on December 10 underwent a colonoscopy which revealed a large circumferential rectal mass approximately 10-cm from the anal verge. Biopsies were obtained with slides reviewed here revealing invasive moderately-differentiated adenocarcinoma.  She was also found to have a 3-cm polyp at 40 cm in the sigmoid.  This appears to have been completely removed by hot snare polypectomy per the colonoscopy report, and pathology here revealed invasive moderately-differentiated adenocarcinoma arising within the tubulovillous adenoma with high-grade dysplasia.  The resection margins could not be evaluated from the specimen.  She also had a-1-cm sigmoid colon polyp which was removed, and our pathology has confirmed this as a hyperplastic polyp.  It was not mentioned that any tattooing was performed.  She has not undergone other restaging studies and is here for definitive treatment. Her colonoscopy was also notable for sigmoid diverticulosis.  She denies a history of diverticulitis
Mrs. Becnel has no family history of colorectal cancer.  She denies rectal or abdominal pain.  Her weight has been stable.  She denies fatigue.  She has had a change in her bowel habits in that over the last three-to-four months she has been going three-to-four times a day when her normal was one-to-two times a day previously.  She is having bloody discharge at times.  Her appetite has been stable.  She has been noticing more flatus.  She denies fecal incontinence but has occasional fecal urgency.  She is not on blood thinners.  .

[end section id="20103"]

